node.text: The latest trend in cushions is rectangular shaped cushions. From small mini rectangles on a small armchair, to mid sized rectangles on a sofa and jumbo sized ones for beds they are a trend set to stay for the long term. I love using them in combination with square shaped cushions, they look so chic layered up and are a great way to add more pattern and texture without taking up too much sitting space on your furniture. #designtrends #cushions

node.text: I wanted to share this as social media can create this false perception of perfection. This video covers how I cope with self doubt as a creative. This angle shows the cooking area and to the right of it a door to the concealed pantry complete with lift from the working / professional kitchen on the floor below. node.text: The cosy TV room from our Hyde Park project. This room transitioned late on in the design process from a guest bedroom into an extra TV room. Luckily we were able to pivot quickly and adapt the designs to suit a new function. A small and cosy room for relaxing no matter how grand your house is, is always the room people are drawn to, it’s so comforting. #sophiepatersoninteriors #cosy #cosylivingroom #darkinteriors 📷 @julian_abrams_photo

node.text: Bouclé headboards and botanical art in this bedroom.  Some of my clients call this wall filler art and some love the fact it quietly adds to the space rather than taking centre stage. I think a combination of original art- paintings, sculpture, prints, dried botanical art like this is a good mix across a home- with the original and statement pieces taking centre stage in the principal rooms and then pieces like this adding to the more secondary areas like guest rooms and kids rooms. Not everything in an interior should make a strong statement otherwise it becomes overkill, somethings should be support pieces. #interiordesign #art 📷 @raymain57

node.text: The beautiful abbey ruin @painshill -the Ruined Abbey sits wistfully by the water’s edge and casts stunning reflections into the serpentine lake. In the 18th century monasteries and abbeys would often produce wine so the architecture compliments the vineyard planted next to it. It was designed to be a ruin to add an air of history and remind the visitor of the past. If you’re looking for a day out this is a beautiful place to spend the day- beautiful views across Surrey and it has a little playground for kids too. Last weekend we went here in the morning then lunch @grappelli_cobham which was the perfect balance of kids activities and a nice lunch for the adults! #painshill #cobham #weekend #thingstodo #daysoutwithkids no ads or gifts just my experience ✨
